Table O.1 and Figure O.3 show the [notional amounts](../Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) of outstanding interest rate [derivatives](../../Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md) across the globe. These [derivatives](../../Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md) are described in later chapters, but [derivatives](../../Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md) essentially allow market participants to take positions on [interest rates](../Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md), whether for [hedging](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md), [investment](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md), or speculative purposes. The notional amount of a derivative is used to calculate the cash flows that one of the derivative's counterparties pays the other. Adding together all [notional amounts](../Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md), however, can significantly overstate market size. First, the largest market participants, namely dealers, tend to be simultaneously long and short nearly identical [derivatives](../../Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md). Second, options are actually equivalent to only fractions of the [notional amounts](../Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) of their [underlying securities](../Chapter%207/Rate%20and%20Price%20Trees.md). Later chapters elaborate on these points, but, for the purposes of this [overview](../../Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Overview%20of%20Financial%20Markets.md), this table and figure are reported in [notional amounts](../Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md).  

While [derivatives](../../Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md) may trade in a particular locality, there is no sense in which [derivatives](../../Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md) are issued in one place or another: local regulations aside, any entity, residing anywhere, can enter into these [derivatives](../../Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md) contracts. A typical classification, therefore, is the [currency](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) in which the cash flows of the derivative are denominated. The first two columns of Table O.1 show [notional amounts](../Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) for swaps, options, and [forward rate agreements](../Chapter%2012/EURIBOR%20Forward%20Rate%20Agreements%20and%20Futures.md). Most of the outstanding amounts are denominated in US Dollars (USD) and Euro (EUR). The quantities in the table hint at the overstatement of market size by notional amount: if the sizes of the markets for these UsD [derivatives](../../Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%209%20Arbitrage%20and%20Hedging%20With%20Options.md) were really $\$150$ trillion, they would be larger than the combined size of all [global debt securities](.md) markets. The second two columns of the table show the [notional amounts](../Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) of standardized, exchange-traded [interest rate futures](../../../Financial%20Engineering/Derivatives/Part%20III%20-%20Fixed%20Income%20Futures%20Contracts/Chapter%2012%20-%20Hedging%20with%20Interest%20Rate%20Futures.md) and options. Amounts outstanding of UsD-denominated contracts are by far the greatest, with those denominated in British Pounds (GBP) and EUR making up most of the rest of the overall market.  

